english:
  title: A Letter Sent on Behalf of the Immortals
  author: Lee Gyeong-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day, the emissaries of the Purple Subtlety Palace—the Cinnabar-Source Immortal and his companions—respectfully dispatch the Golden Attendant to bear this letter to Lee Chun-gyeong of the Eastern Kingdom.

    The human realm teems with clamor and confusion—how arduous it must be for you. Tell us, how fares your pursuit of the Way? We gaze upon you with endless longing.

    We two dwell at the left and right hand of the Jade Emperor, dispensing the mandates of Heaven. Once, you too were a celestial scribe, drafting the Emperor's edicts. In spring, you wove the breath of harmony, nurturing grass and tree. In winter, you commanded the frost's severity, causing ten thousand things to wither. The thunder and wind, the snow and mist—all emanations of Heaven's will upon the realm below—issued forth as perfect expression through your brush. The Emperor cherished your merit and sought to repay your labors. He consulted with us, and we counseled thus: "Let him leave his office in Heaven temporarily. Send him to the human world as a scholar-official, that he might swiftly draft the great decrees in the Western Pavilion, compose the harmonious words in the Purple Ministry. Let his blessings flow to the people, his name resound throughout the cosmos. Then, recalled to Heaven, let him ascend again to the immortal ranks, that his service may be fully rewarded."

    The Emperor granted this wish. He blessed you with temperate spirit and keen brilliance, sending forth a hundred chariots of fortune and ten thousand horses in your wake. Thus were you born in the Eastern Sea, in Fusang's corner where the sun first breaks.

    Years have passed since your descent. Yet we have heard no word of advancement, no new rank obtained, no marvel accomplished, no great work completed to reach the Emperor's ears. This bewilders us greatly. We were about to send an inquiry when one arrived from the human realm. We asked what had become of you, and the messenger replied:

    "This Spring-gyeong has stumbled upon hard fortune, obtaining not even a single minor post. He drowns himself in wine like the exiled immortal, speaking in drunken riddles. He echoes the wanderings of Yuan Jie through mountains and streams, yet wears no official belt at his waist, no cap of rank upon his head. He is like a dragon bereft of water, like a dog homeless and starving—merely a shabby scholar in torn hemp robes. Though the nobles and ministers know his name, they will not employ him, for they deem him impractical and negligent of affairs."

    Before the messenger finished, we started in astonishment and snapped our fingers. We have recorded the crimes of all in your realm who jealously guard against the talented and shun the able, and submitted them sealed to the Emperor. He has nodded his approval and will soon cast such people into great darkness, thus vindicating your wrongs.

    Your wings shall soon unfold. Your steps shall soon ascend. The Jade Hall beckons with open paths—what depth can you not penetrate? The Immortal Registry towers high—what height can you not scale? Let the dusty realm below enjoy its fleeting glory while the dwellers in the emerald heights wait in vain. The jade zither gathers dust, awaiting your fingers to play. The pearl chamber stands empty, awaiting you to open it. The elixir and golden nectar that the Purple Emperor bestowed—we alone have grown weary of drinking them day after day, so long denied the pleasure of sharing them with you.

    Hasten now to fulfill your destined purpose. Rise once more and tread the celestial path.

    Alas, glory cannot remain unfulfilled, nor can wealth be clung to forever. This is our only counsel to you. Exert yourself! We bow our heads in reverence and speak this truthfully.
  footnotes:
    - Lee Chun-gyeong is a poetic name for Lee Gyeong-bo himself; the letter is a creative fiction where heavenly immortals address the poet through this alter ego.
    - The 'exile of the immortal' and references to Yuan Jie evoke Li Bai and other Daoist-inspired poets who rejected official service for wine and nature.
    - The imagery of the dragon without water and the homeless dog reflects the poet's sense of displacement and unfulfilled potential despite his talents.
    - This work blends celestial bureaucracy, Daoist mysticism, and social commentary on court politics, a characteristic device in medieval Korean-Chinese literary culture.
